<user_name>Nathan Delaney</user_name><review>It's been several years since I've been here.  When I lived down the street this was a go to spot and always got a Downtown Burrito.  They went downhill for a bit with their other (since closed) location on santa Rosa.

But they have done a great job making super fresh food.  The food is better than ever and they make it how you want.  Their menu only said breaded fish but we asked if they could do grilled.  They did and it was so good.  It should be a regular menu item.  Also it was great to find out that they prep and cook it there in house.  Great local restaurant with super fresh and delicious food.<//review>< pics>

<time>1467941068333<//time><Rate>4<//Rate><review>Taco Roco is a decent Mexican food place. It's not our favorite in town, but it's convenient. They have a decent vegetarian burrito that is rather healthy (does not use any cheese or sour cream), but it's not the most amazing vegetarian burrito in town. My husband really likes their breaded fish tacos. Their staff is generally pretty nice, and they do have some decent beers available for purchase. Their chips and salsas are generally very good, so make sure to get some of those!<//review>< pics>

Accidentally found this place. Value for your $$ is exceptional. It's quick, friendly, nice and portions are generous. Somewhere between a Taco Bell and a fancy Mexican restaurant. Give it a try!< /review>

< text>
My wife and I wanted to celebrate my birthday on May 29th at Taco Roco. We  knew it was a holiday so we went to Taco Roco on Friday May 26 to ask if they would be open because of the holiday and we even asked if could bring a cake and seat in the back patio at 5pm. They said no problem and yes we will be OPEN!
Well, Sorpresa!! my family and I arrived at 4:40 only to find out that they closed at 3pm.
The next day I went in to speak with Narsi the owner but he was not there, they ask for my name and phone number to be contacted by the owner but nobody called me yet today is June 3. I wanted to talk to the owner before posting my review but after a few attempts with no answer I've decided to post this not so positive review. Nothing against the food because we eat there all of the time but I think that communication fell big time!
At the end we decided to go back home and order take out from Olive Garden.

Never trust when a Mexican says the salsa it's not spicy or when they say they will be open on Memorial Day!!!!

Ponchito< /text>
<Rating>1< /Rating></record>
</dataset><record>

<userid>107155031617192452895< /userid><username>miles anderson< /username><date>1589477521195</date>< rate>
5<//rate>
< text>
What a superb and kind group of rescuers at TAPS. Our beautiful rescue dog Dempsey has been so cared for by the truly nurturing Bonnie, who has answered so many of our questions. If you're concerned their fees are a little high - don't be. They cover vital surgeries and vets' trips during the fostering, and ensure you are comfortable with the pet as well as the pet being happy with you. They really do want the best outcome for the saved animal. This small organization relies on donations: they don't have the facilities of a large shelter - and we were alerted all along to the costs. We are SO glad Dempsey found us through TAPS. And we would wholeheartedly recommend them to others - especially seeing how shelters often find an animal's new owner through lottery. Not here: it's true care. Thank you!< /text>

< Review>
Aside from being wildly over-priced, my biggest concern was that the owner's son didn't like the dogs barking so he would tell at them and spray them in the face with water while they were caged. If you can't handle dogs barking, don't work at a pet rescue. This person seemed untrained and inexperienced in humane animal care. If he did that in front of me, what was going on behind closed doors? It wasn't a good sign. There is another worker there who was very kind and gentle with the animals. It seems these rescues are running a bit of a racket: $700 for a dog? Hm. I love the pup I rescued from the rescue, but I wish the staff was required to have proper training. For that much $$$ they can afford it.

UPDATE: I was mistaken that it was the owner who I had initially talked to (it was a volunteer's son, not the owner's). The owners just called me and said they would correct the problem and speak with the seasonal worker who was spraying the dogs. They sound genuinely concerned. So if you go visit, hopefully things will be different. It sounds like they are open to requiring actual training by any staff working with the animals. Hope so!
The dog I brought home does not seem traumatized or mistreated. He loves people and is friendly and wonderful.</Review>

The Animal Protectorates is a nonprofit animal welfare organization so there are no owners - but staff and a generous group of volunteers who give freely of their time.  Your review deals with 2 separate items - adoption fees (which you feel are too high) and how you may have perceived treatment of the animals at the center.\n\nDuring our conversation, I explained that the reason Operation Adopt is different than other small rescue groups who are home-based or who conduct pop-up adoption events on the weekends is that we have a physical facility.  Running a business like Operation Adopt includes staffing, insurance, rent, worker's comp, utilities, supplies, collars, leashes, harnesses, food, vaccinations, etc.... After our conversation I believe that you understood why the adoption fees are different - they help offset the cost of running the center along with our generous and supportive donors.\n\nI was not physically present during the time you describe an incident occurring. < response>
{'time': 1522683940675, 'text': "Jeremy, we are so glad that your daughter found a kitten.  Pets enrich the lives of people and her getting to grow up care for an animal is wonderful.  We are not exactly sure when you came into Operation Adopt since this review was just written (and we haven't had kittens in quite a while), but nonetheless we are hoping that giving you the reason why we don't allow everyone coming in to hold kittens (or puppies) helps you understand.  We don't allow people to hold them without an application on file for a few reasons.  First, everyone coming in would want to hold them and given that we are a pet adoption center with a large number of animals instead of just a pet supply store like the place you mentioned, we give first priority to people with applications on file because going through the process shows us that people are serious about adopting - not just holding animals - which helps our staff and volunteers know where to focus (because it they had to let everyone hold animals, they wouldn't have time to dedicate tho their primary role of caring for the animals).  Secondly, and most importantly, diseases spread by touch, and young animals are extremely vulnerable.  Let's say for instance someone was looking for a puppy or kitten and had been visiting local shelters and holding multiple animals - and one of those animals had a disease.  Diseases in shelters are sometimes fatal and many are contagious not only to other animals, but humans as well.  So, by allowing anyone coming in to touch or hold animals, we are putting our animals and people at risk.  This is another reason we require people to sanitize their hands prior to interacting with our animals.  We are sure the kitten you adopted is healthy and disease free, but hope you understand that we take a lot of precautions to care for our animals and humans coming into contact with them."}< /response>

{'time': 1516741560397, 'text': 'Shelters use many different methods to adopt animals such as first come, lottery drawing and bidding. When we get to a kill shelter, very rarely are any people there wanting to adopt the same animal. That‚Äôs hardly ever happened.  If it does, and if that particular shelter has an "open and fair" bidding process as set forth in their municipal code, and if our trained staff has already spent hours of time and travel assessing an animal to become part of our adoption process, then we move forward to adopt the animal. That feels both fair and just to us; more importantly, it is in line with our mission to save as many animals as possible from kill shelters and find them the best forever homes while in the process freeing up space to allow more at risk animals additional time to find homes.'}<//resp>

< text>
The people at this place are exceptionally nice and seem to take very good care of the pets. I‚Äôm giving  one star because their model doesn‚Äôt serve any purpose other than satisfying some pretty troubling elitist attitudes regarding shelters and removing ‚Äúhighly adoptable‚Äù dogs from qualified middle and low income adopters. Hear me out.

Based on my visit to their store and information on their website, TAPS selects dogs that have a high probability of adoption, i.e., very cute, young dogs and puppies. I didn‚Äôt see a single pit bull though it‚Äôs possible they have selected some in the past. After adoption from the shelter, TAPS relocates the animal to a spacious and swanky store located in a very popular and very expensive district in Burbank. Once there, the staff sets the dog up for re-adoption the and adds a hefty premium: we‚Äôre taking around $700. For reference, the fee for the same neutered and microchipped dog at the shelter is around $95 or less.

Here‚Äôs why this is problematic. Although TAPS claims its methodology ‚Äúfrees up shelter space,‚Äù it logically would have a minimal effect in achieving that end, given that the dogs they select are the most likely to be adopted, and fastest adopted at the shelter. Moreover, they are intercepting the animals from potential forever homes just for placement in a self-described halfway house. As a representative from TAPS has admitted in a comment to a previous review, they have even adopted animals who already had potential permanent adopters lined up! These methods perpetuate the problem it claims to be solving. So obviously ‚Äúfreeing up space‚Äù or finding forever homes is not their primary goal.

The inflated adoption fee doesn‚Äôt seem to add up either. The shelter staff explained to me that the fee covers surgeries, microchipping, food, and lease payments for the Burbank boutique. Assuming the dogs are neutered/spayed and microchipped at the shelter and are eating moderately priced dog food, the vast majority of their adoption fee is going to their lease. The dogs there seemed healthy, and when I asked about the one dog who seemed to
need surgery, the staff insisted that the issue was cosmetic and would not be covered by the adoption fee. Note: my current dog had the same ‚Äúcosmetic‚Äù issue that later caused her recurring injuries and warranted surgery. Providing needed medical care doesn‚Äôt seem to be the primary goal either.

So, that leaves us with one other remaining goal of TAPS, which is to provide an alternative for ‚Äúpeople who find the shelter experience emotionally upsetting.‚Äù Okay so first of all I don‚Äôt know a single person who fits that description. With the exception of those with PTSD, this is not an issue for most  people. If you‚Äôre unwilling to rescue a dog because you find the shelter experience that unbearable, you probably shouldn‚Äôt have a dog no less have a nonprofit dedicated to your ‚Äústruggle.‚Äù Second, if that is your main goal, get a less expensive boutique to house your adoptable animals so you can make the adoption fee accessible to more income levels and place more animals. You can still bring the dogs to popular areas with lots of foot traffic. The shelters do it all the time.

Finally, the most irksome issue with this place is how class (and race if you want to get deeper) are implicated in its mission. The organization, located in an affluent, mostly white part of LA, skims the shelters, located in the lower-income areas to take the best dogs away from low and middle income community members and potential forever homes so that they can be placed in a temporary shelter and adopted at an inaccessible fee by those with much greater means. Coupled with their aversion to the shelter experience, which perhaps requires a trek into a ‚Äúdirtier‚Äù and less white area, it‚Äôs hard to not feel the subtle undertones of classism (and perhaps racism).

In short, don‚Äôt feel good about yourself if you adopt here.</text>

None< /Pics>
<response>{'time': 1522461801250, 'text': 'Katelyn, it may help you to have background on how Operation Adopt came into existence.  For years, The Animal Protectorates worked on "puppy mill" legislation to stop pet stores in Burbank, California from selling animals coming from commercial breeding facilities.  The alternative business model is to help rehome animals coming from shelters, humane societies or qualified rescue organizations in the same space.  Consumers visiting pet stores selling the commercially bred animals were spending thousands of dollars on purebred animals, having no idea where they were coming from.  We are really excited that these same consumers are finding joy in adopting orphaned animals coming from shelters.  Their mindsets are changing from thinking shelter animals are inferior to making a shelter animal a part of their family.  You are correct that adoption fees at Operation Adopt are higher than they are at a shelter.  This is because there are no subsidies from local agencies to offset the rent, staff salaries (we have to have staff to care for the animals), workers comp insurance, utilities, vet bills, and everything else that comes along with running a pet adoption center.  The perceived value of shelter animals are increasing in peoples minds (and hearts) because we are bringing them into a clean environment where meeting them is easy and supportive.  We also conduct home visits on every adoption to try to insure that these animals lives are headed in a better direction than where they came from (most of the animals we receive are neglected, some matted to the point of not being able to walk comfortably and many have medical issues requiring immediate and continuing vet care to get them to the point they are ready for adoption).  Sometimes though, even our rigorously vetted adopters have circumstances change in their lives that prevent them from keeping their pet.  Our guarantee is that in those circumstances we will receive their animal back and once again try to rehome the animal so that the animal will never enter the shelter again (our Purple Collar Promise to the animal).  So, our mission to that end has a positive impact on reducing the strain on shelters.\nWe hope knowing some more background will give you a different perception.  Thank you for visiting and for your compliment about the staff (we think they are pretty awesome too) and the good care we give the animals while they are with us.  We don\'t take your review as negative, on the contrary, we think all reviews are positive because they help us grow as the most unique adoption center in the country.'}</response>< Gmap_id>

< review>
*CAUTION* READ BEFORE ADOPTING FROM HERE!!!
A few months ago I was on the hunt to find a companion. After searching high and low I found the cutest dog on PetFinder from this rescue and decided to send an email to get more information. I wanted to do the four day foster but Shelley (the owner) denied that. I moved forward and adopted my blind dog Moira however, I had to sign the contract before I ever got to see the records. After having my dog for a day I started noticing that she was panting a lot and sometimes even shaking and this was when we would just be laying on the couch. After finally receiving the records I was livid! The record showed that my dog was ten almost eleven years old BUT online they had her as a five year old puppy! I completely understand that rescues never know an exact age but come on! Cutting down half of an animals age is completely unacceptable! I decided to try not to let that get to me as she was such a sweet animal so I kept her for awhile. The first weekend that I had her I tried to go on a walk and after a short ten minutes she was coughing and breathing so hard that I had to rush her in the house. I was afraid she had sniffed something bad but once she got in and was able to lay down she was fine. So the next day I took her on the same walk and the same thing happened after ten minutes. That is when I realized she was too old and unfortunately I would need to give her back. I sent Shelley an email and she called me one morning and I can honestly tell you Shelley is the most UNPROFESSIONAL person to run a business that I have ran into so far. She was so rude and was cutting me off as I was trying to explain myself and talked to me like I was a child. She then yelled and told me I could bring the dog back and get my money back. The next weekend I took the dog back and Shelley refused to give me my money back stating she had a signed contract which she is right she does however, she LIED about the age of the dog and also had me sign the contract before she sent me the records! Such SHADY business. I decided not to cause a scene at her store so I went home and sent her a very serious email. After going back and forth with me she eventually told me she would discuss this in her next board meeting on Oct 11th and get back to me but the next day I received a call from a lady, Laurie, claiming to be a part of the board but I have yet to find proof of that and she advised they would give me half of my money back IF I signed a nondisclosure agreement. Again SHADY!!! I had them send me the nondisclosure and after review it was completely ridiculous. It states their side with the contract attached but does not state that they LIED about the age. I let Laurie know I would only sign this IF I could add in my part and attach the records but of course they denied that. Shelley stated that they have some vets who stated the dog was eight and another six however they have NO proof that she is five and not to mention the vet records that show she was ten is the shelter that the owner surrendered her too and it has an exact date of birth! I am posting this and will continue to post and warn people and report my experience to the BBB so NO one makes the same mistake I did. Do Not let your excitement get the best of you or trust them because their store is clean or that they do home check ins. Do ALL research and ask for the records BEFORE signing anything. Shelley is an attorney and knows ways around how to scheme and manipulate. OH and not to mention Moira is posted back on PetFinder as five years old which is completely false due to the fact that she will be eleven in two months on December 30th as she was born in 2005. This situation for me was SHADY and a complete FRAUD and Shelley should be ashamed that she lied and then had the nerve to make it seem like I was the issue.
*In response to Shelley's comment, the eye care receipt I received showed they paid $234 for eye care. I kept Moira for a total of 3 weeks. Also, the prescription is NOT the issue, her LYING is! Be careful when adopting here!*< /review>

< Review>
I have a Cervelo R5 that I build from scratch myself.  Once the job was done, I tried to adjust the special wedge system seat clamp but soon realized that it is stuck and it's not going to move.  I took the bike to a very famous bike shop in East Bay to look at it.  After leaving the bike there for a week, they claimed that they worked on it for an entire day and yet no luck.  They also said they called Cervelo and followed their instruction and came to the conclusion that the bike must be shipped back to Cervelo and if determined that it is still under warranty I will get a new frame.  I decided before doing anything else, I have another bike shop take a look and that's when I found Frame Up on google map.  Amazingly enough in less than 15 minutes they manged to pull the wedge clamp out without any damage to the carbon frame.  They also clean the seat post.  I was happiest man on earth at that moment.  They also didn't want to charge me but I felt obligated to pay something.  This is the most professional bike shop in the area hands down.  I will not bother going anywhere else.<//Review>

Henry did such a great job, asked how I liked my nails shaped, how dark I wanted the polish, took the time to actually trim my cuticles and no annoying upselling. <Name>Jeff Dinakar<//Name><resp>None<//resp>< Text>
Sweetheart Cafe is one of the best value Boba places that you'll find in Berkeley. They've got a pretty diverse selections of teas/ milk teas that you can order, but more than likely you'll find that you'll end up with a favorite that you order every time. For me that was the Tapioca Pearl Milk Tea, but I've had friends who prefer other selections as well.

Sweetheart also offers various snacks, I'd definitely recommend the popcorn chicken, as you get a good amount of chicken and adding a bit of chilli powder to it really takes it to the next level. Sweetheart is definitely worth a try at this price point, even if it's not your favorite, it can easily become a staple in your Berkeley Boba world.<//Text>

< Text>
Sidewalk Cafe is awesome. Brian and his aunt, the new owners are laid back and easy-going.

Sidewalk Cafe is a throwback to old fashion cafe's. It's very relaxing and inviting.

My first time here, this afternoon, and Brian recommended the chai tea. The chai tea is way better then the place that has locations on every street corner. The brown maple crunch oatmeal is on-point. The taste and quantity great. The price is reasonable. Parking easy since it's in a small shopping center.

I'm going to recommend Sidewalk Cafe to RBAC water fitness classes.</Text>

<Name>Phil Blum<//Name>< pictures>

<review>Ok, this is a rather unusual review, but here goes:  I know that the coffee at this joint is good, but how good is it?  I was at grave risk of becoming an espresso widow to the Sidewalk Cafe!  My wife loves the espresso here so much that the coffee I made at home could not compete.  It was getting to be that just about every morning, I would wake up to an empty bed.  Yes, she would get up before me and jet up to the Sidewalk Cafe, and STAY THERE until she had had a couple of espressos.  And she'd bring her lap top too, so I know the wifi is great as well, because she would spend hours there getting all her work done!

Finally, I couldn't take this place showing me up.  I broke down and got a quality espresso maker and coffee grinder off Amazon (to the tune of $500!) to woo her back home, and it worked like a charm!  (Whew, lucky for me!  It would have been a bummer if that didn't work!  I'd have to do some serious soul searching...)

So if you find your significant other missing when you wake up in the morning, DON"T PANIC!  And don't take it personally, it is probably just the coffee.  Check the Sidewalk Cafe before you call the police or hospitals, and definitely before accusing him/her of two timing you!

We still drop by to visit for coffee with friends now and then though.  And just in case you aren't ready to spring for $500 worth of espresso gear, this is definitely the place!< /review><Response>None< /Response>< user_id>

< review>
Had an unfortunately lackluster experience at this Del Taco location.

First off, access to getting inside is more difficult than you‚Äôd imagine a restaurant would want it to be‚Äîthe location has two entrances, the easier of which does not have a door handle on the outside. It also can not be ‚Äúpushed‚Äù inward. I watched several patrons use their fingers to dig into the crevice where the door meets the wall to pull the door open. Nonsense.

The staff at the register were okay, but the experience felt more like a hindrance than a welcoming experience. Seating was vast and varied (see pics).

The food. WOOF. My chicken taco had all the cheese on one end of the taco, and all the lettuce on the other. Furthermore, all the SAUCE on the inside was off to one side of the taco as well. You could tell the staff was hurried (not sure why, you can see in the pics there was no one there yet), because my Beyond Burrito was also torn at one end.

I still gave 3 stars because a) Del Taco is the best, and b) this is a fast food restaurant, not a Michelin location. STILL, I would hesitate to come back here so quickly.<//review>

Teresa K.< /Name>
<time>1450251757981< /time>< Rate>
2<//Rate>
< Text>
This is located in a large strip mall with Ross, Safeway, etc., so pretty convenient. FedEx itself is set off to the side of this area so parking tends to be easier. I went on a weekday night at 7pm during holiday season. There were only 2 workers there. I wanted to send a package internationally but there were no instructions -- for instance, there appeared to be a standard international customs form next to the boxes so it stood to reason that's what I needed to fill out. I filled it out and spent 20-30min waiting in line, only to be told that I needed to fill out an entirely different form (that wasn't available in the obvious spot with all the various other forms), AND that my package would cost $100+ to send overseas (this is more than triple the rate of USPS) and there were no alternative pricing options. It was so preposterous that I ended up not sending the package, and found myself having wasted precious time after work and ending up back where I started. To its credit: one star for the awesome FedEx rep who was quite nice and apologized to each customer for the wait; one star for the wide variety of packaging supplies and other interesting office supply goods there. However, I walked away vowing never to use FedEx ever again, if I can help it. I'd have better luck praying upon good ol' Santa Claus to deliver my gifts. Bah humbug.</Text>

<Review>Wait time was long, staff attribute it to COVID restrictions on indoor dining capacity, but it appeared like they were just standing around most of the time; not professional.
Food was decent, for the price. I got a waffle with fruit, and my companion had the avocado toast. They were underwhelmed with their meal, but I enjoyed my meal with a few cups of Black Bear's coffee. We both got drinks and my friend got a side of potatoes. Came out to about $30.
I imagine that if COVID were not as much of a concern, this would have been a much better experience, which is why I gave this place 3 stars. But overall, I'd recommend you go to IHOP, just across the street, unless you want a sweet cream waffle.<//Review>< pics>

< review>
I always love going to the Black Bear Diner! Their portions are large and their prices are reasonable. If you're going with more than two people plan on a wait no matter when you go. If it's just you or you and one other person you can usually get immediate seating if you're willing to sit at the bar stools. In all the years I've been going to Black Bear Diner's across the state, I have never ever had a problem with their food. If you've never been you need to try them!<//review>

< Text>
Black Bear is my favorite go to restaurant when we're on a road trip. This location disappointed both of us. We stopped in around 7 PM on a Sunday expecting the usual stellar experience we have always had at other locations. When we walked in there were several employees at the hostess area but we were not acknowledged or greeted by any of them for what seemed like an eternity. We were seated in a booth in a quiet area. Our drink order was not taken by the host who seated us as it usually is at other locations  and it was several minutes before we saw the waitress. She seemed new and quite nervous as we placed our drink order asking us if we wanted water in our iced tea then corrected herself and asked if we wanted lemon in it. Placing our food order was difficult as the first three items we chose were sold out. My GF settled for the third item on the menu that sounded good to her. I had to settle for the third item also. I don't understand a restaurant being out of signature items so early in the evening. The items were Chicken Pot pie, pot roast and onion rings. I could forgive them being out of one item but three in row is three strikes and you're out! The waitress was sweet and apologetic but poorly trained. This was truly a disappointing experience for us.  Not only was the restaurant out of the food we wanted to order but the meal I settled for was not properly prepared and very disappointing flavor wise.</Text>

Black Bear Diner is always a hit and always busy whenever we come.  Today was opening day for Little League 2018 -- so why not?  Honestly, we were in Buttercream's parking lot -- which didn't have a stall to park in ..so we ended up here.
Party of 3 -- around 11 in the morning .. about a 20 minute wait she says.  I'm telling you, it was packed!  And it was a Saturday haha.  They didn't take longer than maybe 10 minutes -- super quick for them.  We was hangry too.  So hangry my son didn't order from the kids' menu AND he ate all his food.  That almost never happens.  The man had an omelette and one waffle.  The kid had chocolate chip pancakes (2), 2 over easy eggs and bacon.  I had my usual chicken fried steak and eggs with their hash.  We were very pleased .. with the food and the service.  Will we come back?  Heck yes!!<//review>
